article.headline: Kidd leads Nets past ex-assistant coach
article.linkText: Nets drop Wiz on same plays
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- The New Jersey Nets have been running their offense for four years. The Washington Wizards have been trying to learn it for four weeks. The difference in experience made for an unfair fight. The Nets bettered a raw and younger image of themselves Saturday night, beating their former assistant coach in a 98-85 victory over the Wizards. "It's weird to see a team on the other side run the stuff that I like to run, and they're so good at it," said Washington coach Eddie Jordan, who handled the pregame Xs and Os for the past four seasons in New Jersey. "They get backdoors. They get open shots. They get rhythm jump shots. They get bench scores. They're unselfish. They don't care who scores. The object of the offense is to help your teammate first. "They have faith in it, and I don't know if we really quite have the faith in it yet." Jason Kidd had 30 points and nine assists, and Richard Jefferson added 19 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists for the Nets, who never trailed. Brian Scalabrine, starting for injured forward Kenyon Martin, had 12 points. "They need some time under their belt," Kidd said. "It didn't happen for us overnight in the first year that we ran it. We didn't look good on some nights." New Jersey coach Byron Scott improved to 129-120 as the Nets' coach, tying Kevin Loughery (1976-81) for most wins in franchise history. Before the game, Jordan said it was like "fighting your big brother" to face his old team as a head coach for the first time. He not only brought the same plays to Washington, but he calls them by the same names. But New Jersey's familiarity with the system was obvious from the opening whistle. The Nets moved on instinct; the Wizards were a half-step slower. Jordan had to use his bench extensively because he said the starters weren't following the game plan. "You can't compare the two teams," said point guard Gilbert Arenas, who had five of Washington's 22 turnovers. "They have an All-Star point guard. They all know the system, and we're still trying to get the knicks and knacks of the system. They can throw the ball anywhere they want, because they know where each other is going to be." Rookie forward Jarvis Hayes scored 16 points to lead the Wizards. Martin sprained his left ankle in Friday night's victory over Minnesota. Scott did not give a timetable for Martin's return, saying only that the forward is doubtful for Tuesday's game against Houston. The Nets led by seven after the first quarter and by nine at the half, but the Wizards stayed within striking distance until the final four minutes. Hayes had the early hot hand with his jumper, but 13 first-half turnovers kept Washington from seizing any momentum. The Nets opened a 14-point lead in the third quarter before the Wizards closed the period with a 12-2 run capped by Juan Dixon's runner at the buzzer to make it 69-65. The Nets opened the fourth with the 9-2 run, including back-to-back 3-pointers from Kidd. Kidd later started a fast break with a steal, made a behind-the-back pass and finished the sequence by putting in the rebound off a missed shot. Asked what it was like to finally coach against Kidd, Jordan said: "It's like daggers all over your body -- the heart, the back and neck. He just hits you and hurts you in so many different ways."

Game notes
This was the first regular season home game for the Wizards in the post-Michael Jordan era, and the empty seats made it clear that the team is no longer must-see entertainment. A sellout was announced, extending the team record streak to 83, but there were several empty patches in the lower and middle sections. ... Health and Human Services Secretary Tommy Thompson watched the game from Wizards owner Abe Pollin's box. ... New Jersey's Jason Collins got a technical for a taunting "Hulk"-like gesture after a driving dunk in the third quarter.
